  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad and well-established consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is widely recognized as a criminal activity across the globe, and it is explicitly prohibited by laws and regulations in virtually every country. The purpose of these laws is to prevent the integration of illicitly obtained funds into the legitimate financial system, which often serves as a means to conceal the origins of money derived from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and other forms of organized crime.\n\nInternational frameworks, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), have been instrumental in setting global standards for combating money laundering. Additionally, many countries have implemented their own domestic laws and regulations to criminalize money laundering and establish mechanisms for its detection, prevention, and prosecution. For example, in the United States, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act are key pieces of legislation aimed at combating money laundering. Similarly, the European Union has its own Anti-Money Laundering Directives that member states are required to implement.\n\nOverall, the prohibition of money laundering is a cornerstone of efforts to maintain the integrity of financial systems and combat crime, and it is universally regarded as illegal under both national and international law.",
